SP  - 643
EP  - 654
VL  - 45
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1990.tb03709.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper investigates the relationship between bank ownership structure and risk taking. It is hypothesized that stockholder controlled banks have incentives to take higher risk than managerially controlled banks and that these differences in risk become more pronounced in periods of deregulation. In support of this hypothesis, we show that stockholder controlled banks exhibit significantly higher risk taking behavior than managerially controlled banks during the 1979?1982 period of relative deregulation.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - International Interest Rates, Exchange Rates, and the Stochastic Structure of Supply
AU  - BOYLE, GLENN W.
Y1  - 1990/06/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1990.tb03710.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
